<article title='Crete_Senesi'><paragraph><link><target>Image:Crete senesi presso asciano, 09.JPG</target><part>thumb</part><part>right</part><part>Landscape.</part></link>The<space/><bold>Crete Senesi</bold><space/>refers to an area of the<space/><link><target>Italy</target><part>Italian</part></link><space/>region of<space/><link><target>Tuscany</target></link><space/>to the south of<space/><link><target>Siena</target></link>. It consists of a range of hills and woods among villages and includes the<space/><italics><link><target>comuni</target></link></italics><space/>of<space/><link><target>Asciano</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Buonconvento</target></link>,<link><target>Monteroni d'Arbia</target></link>,<link><target>Rapolano Terme</target></link><space/>and<link><target>San Giovanni d'Asso</target></link>, all within the<space/><link><target>province of Siena</target></link>.</paragraph><paragraph><italics>Crete senesi</italics><space/>are literally<space/><link><target>Siena</target><part>Senese</part></link><space/><link><target>clay</target><trail>s</trail></link>, and the distinctive grey colouration of the soil gives the landscape an appearance often described as lunar. This characteristic clay, known as<space/><italics>mattaione</italics>, represents the sediments of the<space/><link><target>Pliocene</target></link><space/>sea which covered the area between 2.5 and 4.5 million years ago. Nearby is also the semi-arid area known as the<space/><link><target>Accona Desert</target></link>.</paragraph><paragraph>Perhaps the most notable edifice of this area is the monastery of<space/><link><target>Monte Oliveto Maggiore</target></link>.</paragraph><paragraph>The region is known for its production of<space/><link><target>white truffles</target></link>, and hosts a festival and a museum dedicated to the rare fungus (genus Tuber).</paragraph><paragraph><table style='border-collapse: collapse; border: 1px solid grey;'><tablerow><tablecell valign="top" align="left"><link><target>Image:Cretesenesi_fieno.jpg</target><part>thumb</part><part>center</part><part></part></link><xhtml:br></xhtml:br><xhtml:center>Cereal crops are cultivated with the aid of irrigation</xhtml:center></tablecell><tablecell valign="top" align="left"><link><target>Image:Cretesenesi_panorama.jpg</target><part>thumb</part><part>center</part><part></part></link><xhtml:br></xhtml:br><xhtml:center>Panorama</xhtml:center></tablecell><tablecell valign="top" align="left"><link><target>Image:Monteolivetomaggiore02.jpg</target><part>thumb</part><part>center</part><part></part></link><xhtml:br></xhtml:br><xhtml:center><link><target>Monte Oliveto Maggiore</target></link></xhtml:center></tablecell></tablerow></table></paragraph><heading level='2'>External links</heading><list type='bullet'><listitem><link type='external' href='http://www.cretesenesi.com/en/'>official '''Crete Senesi''' website</link></listitem><listitem><link type='external' href='http://www.terresiena.it/page.asp?cat=cretesenesi&amp;amp;par=&amp;amp;id_codicearea=cs&amp;amp;lang=en'>Terre di Siena: Crete Senesi</link></listitem><listitem><link type='external' href='http://tuscany.podtravels.tv/category/siena/crete-senesi/'>Videos of the Crete Senesi</link></listitem><listitem><link type='external' href='http://www.borghiditoscana.net/eng/tuscany/siena/cretesenesi/index.html'>Crete Senesi Landscape</link></listitem></list><paragraph><template><target>-</target></template></paragraph><paragraph><template><target>coord</target><arg>43</arg><arg>12</arg><arg>N</arg><arg>11</arg><arg>34</arg><arg>E</arg><arg>type:landmark_region:IT_source:dewiki</arg><arg name="display">title</arg></template></paragraph><paragraph><template><target>-</target></template></paragraph><paragraph><template><target>Authority control</target></template><link><target>Category:Crete Senesi</target><part>01</part></link><link><target>Category:Geography of Tuscany</target></link><link><target>Category:Province of Florence</targe